      "writtenOn": "2019-08-10T05:47:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is there any consideration for using double instead of integer for timestamp? IIRC there are some other parts of emulator using int64 or uint64_t for timestamp (in nanoseconds) -- e.g. getting the current timestamp from looper. It may not be a good idea to have timestamps in two different types.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 190,
        "startChar": 25,
        "endLine": 190,
        "endChar": 41
      },
      "revId": "dd49b9b1a087101452befc52ebce539cc0066525",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1cbc3ba2_f2a8dc9b",
        "filename": "android/android-emu/android/recording/video/player/VideoPlayer.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 190,
      "author": {
        "id": 1508769
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-13T18:22:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Good point! However, the field in offworld.proto is a float that represents timestamp in seconds; the clocks used in the video player also store time as double, so I kept made it consistent with these internal timestamp representations in the video player.",
      "parentUuid": "36cd1631_4ccc0674",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 190,
        "startChar": 25,
        "endLine": 190,
        "endChar": 41
